// Check the OPTIONS 204 response — sendJson is used with status=204.
// sendJson does: const hasBody = status !== 204; body = hasBody ? JSON.stringify(payload) : '';
// So for OPTIONS with 204, no body is written. 
// But content-type header is still set to application/json even for 204.
// RFC 9110: 204 must not include a message body. 
// Setting Content-Type on a 204 is technically incorrect but harmless in practice.
// Most CORS preflight clients ignore the Content-Type on a 204.
// Also: RFC 9110 section 9.3.5 says 204 responses have no content — setting Content-Type is a minor violation.
// Is this new to this branch? Check: all OPTIONS handlers use sendJson(res, 204, {}, ...)
// This pattern existed in main too, so pre-existing, not in scope.

console.log('OPTIONS 204 Content-Type: pre-existing pattern, not new to branch');

// Check: does OPTIONS correctly suppress CORS-required headers?
// sendJson adds access-control-allow-origin, access-control-allow-methods, access-control-allow-headers
// for 204 preflight. That's correct.
console.log('OPTIONS CORS headers: correctly included via corsHeaders in sendJson');
EOF

